Boil a half-full #kettle{}. Halve, peel and thinly slice the @echalion shallot{1}.

Pour the boiled water into a large #saucepan{} with @salt{1/4%tsp} on high heat.

Add the @jasmine rice{150%g} and cook for ~{12-13%minutes}.

Once the rice is cooked, drain in a #sieve{} and pop back in the pan. Cover with a #lid{} and leave to the side until ready to serve.

While the rice cooks, heat a drizzle of @oil{} in a large #frying pan{} on medium-high heat.

Once hot, add the @diced British chicken breast{150%g} and shallot to the pan.

Fry until the chicken is golden brown on the outside and cooked through, ~{8-10%minutes}.

> IMPORTANT: Wash your hands and equipment after handling raw chicken and its packaging. It's cooked when no longer pink in the middle.

Meanwhile, peel and grate the @garlic{2%cloves} (or use a #garlic press{}).

Halve the @sugar snap peas{80%g} widthways.

When the chicken is cooked, drain the prawns, then add them to the pan with the garlic and sugar snaps to the frying pan.

Stir-fry until the sugar snaps are just tender, ~{2-3%minutes}.

> IMPORTANT: Wash your hands and equipment after handling raw prawns.

Stir the @teriyaki sauce{75%g}, @sambal paste{15%g} (add less if you'd prefer things milder), @water{50%ml}(for the sauce) and half the @roasted white sesame seeds{5%g} into the pan.

Simmer until the @king prawns{150%g} are cooked and the sauce is slightly thickened, ~{2-3%minutes}, then remove from the heat. Taste and season if needed.

> Add a splash more water if you feel it needs it. The prawns are cooked when pink on the outside and opaque in the middle.

Fluff up the rice with a #fork{} and share between your #bowls{}.

Top with the sambal teriyaki prawn and chicken stir-fry.

Finish by scattering over the remaining sesame seeds.

Enjoy!